---

<Base
  title={title}
  description={description}
  schema={schema}
  canonical="https://geooptimised.com/geo-explained/"
  ogType="article"
>

  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="container-wide pt-8">
    <ol class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-1.5 font-mono text-xs text-ink-300">
      <li><a href="/" class="transition hover:text-[var(--accent)]">Home</a></li>
      <li aria-hidden="true" class="text-ink-600">/</li>
      <li><a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="transition hover:text-[var(--accent)]">Generative Engine Optimisation</a></li>
      <li aria-hidden="true" class="text-ink-600">/</li>
      <li class="text-ink-200" aria-current="page">GEO Explained</li>
    </ol>
  </nav>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="hero-fade">
    <div class="container-wide pt-16 pb-14">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
        <span class="eyebrow">Beginner's Guide</span>
        <span class="font-mono text-xs text-ink-300">7 June 2026</span>
        <span class="font-mono text-xs text-ink-300">9 min read</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-5 max-w-3xl font-display text-4xl font-bold leading-tight grad-text md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl">
        GEO Explained: A Plain-English Guide
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-200">
        No jargon, no assumed knowledge. If you have heard "GEO" and want to understand what it actually means for your business — and why it is different from the SEO you already know — this guide starts from the beginning.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Two-column: TOC sidebar + main content -->
  <div class="container-wide py-12 lg:grid lg:grid-cols-[220px_1fr] lg:gap-12">

    <!-- Sticky TOC sidebar -->
    <aside class="hidden lg:block">
      <div class="sticky top-24">
        <span class="eyebrow">On this page</span>
        <nav class="toc mt-4 flex flex-col gap-0.5" aria-label="Table of contents">
          {tocItems.map(item => (
            <a href={`#${item.id}`} data-toc-link>{item.label}</a>
          ))}
        </nav>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <!-- Main content -->
    <div>

      <!-- Plain-English intro callout -->
      <div class="card p-6 mb-12 border-l-2 border-[var(--accent)]">
        <p class="eyebrow mb-2">Plain-English Summary</p>
        <p class="text-ink-200 leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-white">GEO (Generative Engine Optimisation) is the practice of making your brand appear in AI-written answers</strong> — the kind you see in Google's AI Overview, or when you ask ChatGPT a question. Think of it as SEO for the AI era: instead of ranking in a list of links, you are aiming to be <em>cited</em> in a generated response.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 1: What Is GEO, Simply? -->
      <section id="what-is-geo" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>What Is GEO, Simply?</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Generative Engine Optimisation (GEO) is the practice of ensuring your business gets mentioned — or "cited" — when AI tools write answers to relevant questions.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          Here is a simple analogy. Imagine a very well-read research assistant who has read most of the internet. When someone asks that assistant "what are the best accountants for small businesses in Manchester?", the assistant writes a short, confident answer and names a few firms. GEO is the discipline of making sure your firm is one of the ones named.
        </p>

        <p>
          That research assistant is, in reality, AI tools like Google's AI Overview, ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Microsoft Copilot. Millions of people are now using these tools to find businesses, get advice, and make decisions — and the businesses that appear in those AI-written answers are gaining a significant visibility advantage over those that do not.
        </p>

        <p>
          For a more formal definition with technical depth, see both our <a href="/geo-definition/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO definition page</a> and the <a href="/what-is-geo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">what is GEO guide</a>. This page focuses on the plain-English explanation first.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2: How Search Changed -->
      <section id="how-search-changed" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>How Search Changed — and Why It Matters</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>For about two decades, "getting found online" meant one thing: ranking in Google's list of blue links.</strong> You worked to appear on page one. Users clicked your link. You got traffic.
        </p>

        <p>
          That model still exists — but something new has been placed in front of it. When you search Google today, the first thing you often see is an AI-generated summary that answers your question directly. No clicking required. Google writes the answer, names a couple of sources, and the user moves on. They may never look at the list of blue links below.
        </p>

        <h3>The Library Analogy</h3>
        <p>
          Think of the old search engine as a card catalogue in a library. It told you which books contained relevant information and roughly where to find them. You still had to go find the book yourself.
        </p>
        <p>
          The new AI search is like having a knowledgeable librarian on duty. You ask a question; the librarian reads several books and gives you the answer directly, mentioning which books they drew from. The books they mention get credibility. The ones they do not mention might as well not exist — for that conversation, at least.
        </p>
        <p>
          GEO is the work of ensuring your content is the kind the librarian trusts, cites, and recommends.
        </p>

        <h3>It Is Not Just Google</h3>
        <p>
          The shift is happening across multiple platforms simultaneously. ChatGPT is used by hundreds of millions of people to research purchases, understand options, and find services. Perplexity has built a following among professionals and researchers who want cited answers quickly. Microsoft Copilot is built into Windows, Office, and Edge, making it the default AI assistant for many workers. Gemini is integrated across Google's own products.
        </p>
        <p>
          Each of these platforms produces AI-written answers. Each of them cites some businesses and ignores others. GEO is the discipline of being among the cited ones.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3: How GEO Works, Simply -->
      <section id="how-geo-works-simply" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>How GEO Works: The Simple Version</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>AI tools decide which businesses and sources to mention based on three main things: how clearly your brand is defined online, how well-structured your content is, and how much external evidence of your authority exists.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          Here is each one explained without the jargon:
        </p>

        <h3>1. How Clearly Your Brand Is Defined</h3>
        <p>
          AI tools learn from a huge range of sources across the internet — not just your own website. They form an understanding of what your business is and what it does based on how consistently that information appears across different places: your website, LinkedIn, industry directories, news coverage, Crunchbase, Wikipedia, and more.
        </p>
        <p>
          If your brand is described differently in different places, or barely mentioned outside your own site, AI tools treat it as low-authority and tend to skip it. The more consistently and prominently your brand appears across authoritative sources, the more confidently AI tools will name you.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is sometimes called "entity authority" — think of an "entity" as simply the AI's concept of your brand. Building entity authority means making sure that concept is clear, consistent, and well-connected to relevant topics.
        </p>

        <h3>2. How Well-Structured Your Content Is</h3>
        <p>
          AI tools extract specific passages from web pages, not whole pages. They are looking for clear, confident statements they can quote or summarise. Content that buries the main point in several paragraphs of background is hard to extract from. Content that starts with a direct, confident answer — and then provides supporting detail — is far easier.
        </p>
        <p>
          Imagine the difference between a colleague who answers your question immediately and directly, versus one who spends three minutes giving context before getting to the point. AI tools prefer the direct colleague.
        </p>

        <h3>3. How Much External Evidence of Authority Exists</h3>
        <p>
          AI tools also look for signals that other authoritative sources agree your business is credible. This includes things like being mentioned in trade publications, being listed in reputable directories, having a Wikipedia entry, or being cited in academic or industry research. These are not unlike the trust signals that traditional SEO also values — they simply operate at a different level for AI citation.
        </p>

        <p>
          For the technical detail behind these mechanisms, see our <a href="/how-geo-works/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">in-depth guide to how GEO works</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4: Why It Matters -->
      <section id="why-it-matters" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark mb-6">
          <h2>Why GEO Matters for Your Business</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>The businesses that get mentioned in AI answers are winning consideration before the buyer has visited a single website.</strong> That is the commercial case for GEO in one sentence.
          </p>
          <p>
            To make it more concrete, here are the scenarios where AI search visibility has a direct impact:
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">B2B Research and Procurement</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Business buyers increasingly start their research with an AI tool. "What software should we use for HR management?" or "Which agencies specialise in financial services content?" are the kinds of questions that now get AI-generated answers before a search results page. Brands cited in those answers earn a first-mover credibility advantage that is difficult to overcome later in the sales process.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Local and Professional Services</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              AI tools are already answering questions like "best solicitors for employment disputes in Birmingham" or "top accountants for sole traders in London." Local professionals and service firms that have established AI visibility for their category and location appear in these answers. Those that have not invested in GEO are simply absent from the recommendation.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Consumer Research Before Purchase</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Consumers asking "what's the best broadband provider for heavy users?" or "which skincare brands are good for sensitive skin?" receive AI-generated answers that name specific brands. Those brands gain visibility and trust at the moment of decision. This is zero-click visibility — your brand is recommended without the user ever having visited your site.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Voice Assistants and Embedded AI</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Voice queries through smart speakers, car systems, and phone assistants return a single spoken answer — there is no page two, no "also worth considering." Either your brand is the answer, or it is not mentioned at all. GEO is the only route to voice search visibility for non-branded queries.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- GEO vs SEO Table (simple version) -->
      <section id="geo-vs-seo-simple" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark mb-6">
          <h2>GEO vs SEO at a Glance</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>GEO and traditional SEO are not the same thing, but they are not opposites either — one builds on the other.</strong>
            Here is the simplest comparison:
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-left text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line)]">
                <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-3 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--accent)]">Question</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-3 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--accent)]">Traditional SEO</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-3 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--accent)]">GEO</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-ink-300">
              <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line-soft)]">
                <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100">What is the goal?</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3">Appear in the list of links</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3">Be named in the AI's written answer</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line-soft)]">
                <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100">How do you win?</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3">High-ranking position in results</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3">Being cited as a trusted source</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line-soft)]">
                <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100">What matters most?</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3">Links from other websites, keywords</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3">How clearly your brand is defined online</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line-soft)]">
                <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100">How many can win?</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3">Ten results on page one</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3">One to three citations per AI answer</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line-soft)]">
                <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100">Does the user click?</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3">Yes — that is the whole point</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3">Sometimes — but brand exposure happens either way</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100">Do you need both?</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3">Yes — SEO is still important</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3">Yes — GEO builds on SEO foundations</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <div class="prose-dark mt-6">
          <p>
            The key point is the last row: you need both. A good SEO foundation makes GEO easier — search engines and AI retrieval systems share many of the same signals for authority and trustworthiness. But SEO alone is not sufficient for AI search visibility. For a more detailed breakdown, see our <a href="/geo-vs-seo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO vs SEO guide</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6: Where to Begin -->
      <section id="getting-started-simple" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Where to Begin with GEO</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The best starting point is to understand where you currently stand in AI search — before investing time or budget in optimisation.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          You can do a basic audit yourself in about thirty minutes. Pick five to ten questions that your ideal customers might ask an AI tool — questions that relate to what you do. Then ask those questions across ChatGPT, Google's AI Overview, and Perplexity. Note whether your brand appears in any answers, and which competitors do.
        </p>

        <p>
          What you find will usually fall into one of three categories:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>You appear consistently.</strong> Good — there is a baseline to build from. The next step is to identify queries where competitors are cited and you are not, and close those gaps.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>You appear occasionally.</strong> This is common for brands with decent SEO but no specific GEO work. Your content is being retrieved but not consistently selected for citation. Structural and schema improvements typically have the most impact here.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>You do not appear at all.</strong> This usually indicates a gap in entity authority — AI tools do not have enough consistent information about your brand from enough authoritative sources to cite you with confidence. Entity building is the priority.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          From there, the path forward follows a structured methodology. The <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">full GEO guide</a> walks through the seven-step framework used by GEOoptimised practitioners. If you want specialist support — or want an expert to run the audit for you — our <a href="/geo-services/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO services</a> start with exactly that. Or <a href="/contact/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">get in touch</a> to discuss your specific situation.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- FAQ Accordion -->
      <div class="prose-dark mt-4">
        <h2 id="faq" class="anchor-top">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 space-y-2" id="faq-accordion">
        {faqs.map(faq => (
          <div class="card overflow-hidden" data-faq>
            <button
              type="button"
              class="flex w-full items-center justify-between p-5 text-left text-sm font-semibold text-white transition hover:bg-white/[.02]"
              aria-expanded="false"
              data-faq-trigger
            >
              <span>{faq.q}</span>
              <span class="faq-icon ml-4 shrink-0 text-[var(--accent)] transition-transform duration-200" data-faq-icon>+</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-body max-h-0 overflow-hidden transition-[max-height] duration-300 ease-in-out" data-faq-panel>
              <p class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300" set:html={faq.a}></p>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <!-- Related Reading -->
      <div class="mt-16" id="related">
        <span class="eyebrow">Go deeper</span>
        <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
          {related.map(item => (
            <a href={item.href} class="card card-hover block p-5 no-underline">
              <span class="eyebrow">{item.tag}</span>
              <h3 class="mt-2 font-display text-base font-semibold text-white">{item.title}</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300">{item.excerpt}</p>
              <span class="mt-3 inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sm text-[var(--accent)]">Read article <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span></span>
            </a>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- CTA Banner -->
  <section class="border-t border-[var(--line)] mt-12 relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="dot-grid absolute inset-0 opacity-40" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="container-wide relative py-20 text-center">
      <span class="eyebrow">Ready to Start?</span>
      <h2 class="mt-4 font-display text-3xl font-bold grad-text md:text-4xl">Find Out How Your Brand Appears in AI Search</h2>
      <p class="mx-auto mt-5 max-w-xl text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">
        GEOoptimised runs AI visibility audits that show exactly where your brand is cited, where it is absent, and which competitors are getting the mentions you should be getting. It is the clearest possible starting point for a GEO strategy.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-8 flex flex-col items-center gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:justify-center">
        <a href="/contact/" class="btn btn-primary">Request an AI visibility audit</a>
        <a href="/geo-services/" class="btn btn-ghost">View GEO services</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Accordion JS -->
  <script>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const triggers = document.querySelectorAll('[data-faq-trigger]');
      triggers.forEach(btn => {
        btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
          const faq = btn.closest('[data-faq]');
          const panel = faq.querySelector('[data-faq-panel]');
          const icon = faq.querySelector('[data-faq-icon]');
          const isOpen = btn.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';

          document.querySelectorAll('[data-faq]').forEach(item => {
            item.querySelector('[data-faq-trigger]').setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'false');
            item.querySelector('[data-faq-panel]').style.maxHeight = '0';
            item.querySelector('[data-faq-icon]').style.transform = 'rotate(0deg)';
          });

          if (!isOpen) {
            btn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'true');
            panel.style.maxHeight = panel.scrollHeight + 'px';
            icon.style.transform = 'rotate(45deg)';
          }
        });
      });
    });
  </script>

  <!-- TOC IntersectionObserver -->
  <script>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const links = document.querySelectorAll('[data-toc-link]');
      if (!links.length) return;
      const ids = Array.from(links).map(a => a.getAttribute('href').slice(1));
      const sections = ids.map(id => document.getElementById(id)).filter(Boolean);

      const observer = new IntersectionObserver(entries => {
        entries.forEach(entry => {
          if (entry.isIntersecting) {
            links.forEach(l => l.classList.remove('active'));
            const active = document.querySelector(`[data-toc-link][href="#${entry.target.id}"]`);
            if (active) active.classList.add('active');
          }
        });
      }, { rootMargin: '-80px 0px -60% 0px', threshold: 0 });

      sections.forEach(s => observer.observe(s));
    });
  </script>

</Base>
